## JavaScript Debounce Function

A debounce function delays executing a function until after a specified wait time has elapsed since the last time it was called.

```javascript
// Debounce function
function debounce(fn, delay) {
  let timer;
  return function (...args) {
    clearTimeout(timer);
    timer = setTimeout(() => fn.apply(this, args), delay);
  };
}

// --- Example Usage ---

// Simulates a search input that only fires after the user stops typing for 300ms
const handleSearch = debounce((query) => {
  console.log(`Searching for: "${query}"`);
}, 300);

// Simulating rapid keystrokes
handleSearch("r");        // cancelled
handleSearch("re");       // cancelled
handleSearch("rea");      // cancelled
handleSearch("react");    // ✅ fires after 300ms — logs: Searching for: "react"
```

### How it works

| Step | What happens |
|------|-------------|
| 1 | A new call comes in and clears the previous timer |
| 2 | A fresh timer is started with the given delay |
| 3 | If no new call arrives before the timer expires, the function runs |
| 4 | If a new call arrives, the timer resets and the cycle repeats |

> **Common use cases:** search inputs, window resize handlers, and button click protection.
